   "source": [
    "Reversed Iteration - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "ff6c314a-f100-4763-97e1-df7d93174b4c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterating a sequence in reverse order\n",
    "\n",
    "If we have a sequence type, then iterating over the sequence in reverse order is quite simple\n",
    "\n",
    "for item in seq[::-1]:\n",
    "    print(item)\n",
    "\n",
    "This works but is wasteful because it makes a copy of the sequence\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(len(seq)):\n",
    "    print(seq[len(seq) - i - 1])\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(len(seq)-1, -1, -1):\n",
    "    print(seq[i])\n",
    "\n",
    "This is more efficient but syntax is messy\n",
    "\n",
    "for item in reversed(seq):\n",
    "    print(item)\n",
    "\n",
    "This is cleaner and just as efficient becuause it creates an iterator that will iterate backwards over the sequence\n",
    "It does not copy the data like the first example\n",
    "\n",
    "Both __getitem__ and __len__ must be implemented\n",
    "We can override how reversed works by implementing the __reversed__ special method"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "8692fa03-0cd7-4025-a3b3-25e6ec5a1378",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterating an iterable in reverse\n",
    "\n",
    "Unfortunately, reversed() will not work with custom iterables without a bit of extra work\n",
    "When we call reversed() on custom iterable, Python will look for __reversed__ function\n",
    "That function should return an iterator that will be used to perform the reversed iteration\n",
    "\n",
    "So basically we have to implement a reverse iterator ourselves\n",
    "Just like the iter() method, when we call reversed() on an object:\n",
    "- looks for and calls __reversed__ method\n",
    "- if not uses __getitem__ and __len__ to create an iterator for us\n",
    "- exception otherwise"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "23fa0304-5f7a-47cb-91ac-a6bfe1953d9d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Card Deck Example\n",
    "\n",
    "In code exercise I am going to build an iterable containing a deck of 52 sorted cards\n",
    "2 spaces...ace spades, 2 hearts...ace hearts, 2 diamonds...ace diamonds, 2 clubs...ace clubs\n",
    "Don't want to create a list containing all pre-created cards -> Lazy Evaluation\n",
    "So I want iterator to figure out the suit and card name for a given index in the sorted deck\n",
    "\n",
    "SUITS = ['Spades', 'Hearts', 'Diamonds', 'Clubs']\n",
    "RANKS = [2, 3, 4, ..., 10, 'J', 'Q', 'K', 'A']\n",
    "\n",
    "We assume deck is sorted as follows\n",
    "- iterate over suits\n",
    "- for each suit iterate over ranks\n",
    "- card = combination of suit and rank\n",
    "\n",
    "2S...AS, 2H...AH, 2D...AD, 2C...AC\n",
    "\n",
    "There are len(SUITS) suits -> 4\n",
    "There are len(RANKS) ranks -> 13\n",
    "The deck has a length of: len(SUITS)*len(RANKS) -> 52\n",
    "Each card in this deck has a positional index: a number from 0 to len(deck) - 1 -> 0-51\n",
    "To find the suit index of a card at index i: i // len(RANKS)\n",
    "\n",
    "Examples/\n",
    "5th card (6S) -> index 4\n",
    "-> 4 // 13 -> 0\n",
    "16th card (4H) -> index 15\n",
    "-> 15 // 13 -> 1\n",
    "\n",
    "To find the rank index of a card at index i: i % len(RANKS)\n",
    "\n",
    "Examples/\n",
    "5th card (6S) -> index 4\n",
    "-> 4 % 13 -> 4\n",
    "16th card (4H) -> index 15\n",
    "-> 15 % 13 -> 2"
   ]
  },
